{East considered Blackwood, then realized if West showed either 2 or 3 Aces he was going to bid slam. But if West showed just one Ace he would have to maneuver to play 5NT which might be worse than 6\C. So he just bid the slam. East plays 6\C. South leads the \SJ.

You wish, you hope, you may even pray, but when you play the \SQ North covers with the \SK. So you know you have a \S loser. And unless North holds the \DQ you might have a \D loser also.

Perhaps an elimination play will improve your chances. Don't lead a trump yet though, you're going to need several entries to dummy to eliminate the \Hs. 

Win the \S, play to the \HA and ruff a \H.

Play a trump to dummy's \CJ (both defenders follow) and ruff another \H high.

Play to dummy's \CA, pulling their last trump, and ruff the last \H.

Now execute the throw-in by leading a \S. If South wins the trick he will have to play \Ds for you or give you a ruff-sluff. So if these are competent defenders they will make sure that it is <b>NORTH</b> who wins the \S trick. So he does, and he plays a small \D.

<b>DO NOT PLAY THE JACK!</b> If the finesse is going to work now it will still work one trick later. By playing low you take advantage of the possibility that North held the \D10 and South will have to put on the \DQ to prevent you taking a trick with dummy's \D9.

Many elimination endings give you a sure thing. Others just improve your chances.  

Here you had two chances. First, South might have HAD to win the throw-in, either because he had all of the high \Ss, or more likely because he messed up. The second chance paid off when North took the throw-in but you found a fortunate position with the \Ds.}
[Play "W"]SJ

